# Keybind Optimizer - Coding Standards

## Svelte Syntax Rules
- Always use Svelte 4 syntax (Options API). Never use Runes.
- DO NOT use Svelte 5 "Runes" ($state, $derived, $effect, $props).
- Use standard `let` variables for component state.
- Use `export let` for component props.
- Use Svelte stores (`writable`, `derived`, `readable`) for shared state.

## TypeScript Rules
- Use TypeScript interfaces for all data structures.
- Prefer functional composition over classes.
- Define explicit types for function parameters and return values.
- Place interfaces in dedicated type files (e.g., `src/lib/types/`).

## Styling Rules
- For styling, use DaisyUI utility classes (e.g., btn, card, range, input) first.
- Then use Tailwind utilities for custom styling.
- Use DaisyUI theme variables for consistent theming.
- Avoid inline styles; prefer utility classes.

## State Management
- Use LocalStorage for persistence via Svelte stores.
- Create dedicated store files in `src/lib/stores/`.
- Use `derived` stores for computed values.

## Component Structure
- Keep components small and focused.
- Use `+page.svelte` for route pages.
- Use `+layout.svelte` for shared layouts.
- Place reusable components in `src/lib/components/`.

## Drag and Drop
- Use `svelte-dnd-action` for all drag-and-drop functionality.
- Ensure Svelte 4 compatibility (no Runes).

## AI Integration
- Use Vercel AI SDK (ai package) v3 for AI features.
- Use OpenAI SDK v4 for API interactions.
